And here aptly enough comes up the name of one who, like Barclay, was a physician, a poet, and an Aberdonian—ArthurJohnston. His literary char- acteristics have a curious parallel with those of Ausonius, who was a physician of Bordeaux. Both seem to have turned aside from the ordinary topics of heroic or lyric poetry to indulge in genia} reminiscences of the men or the places they were personally interested in.
